"# Chapter 5 — The Frame

You have been talking to Motoi through the terminal. Now you talk to him through the screen. Every picture Motoi draws lives in a frame — a rectangular grid of pixels the runtime holds for you. This chapter takes you from `no picture` to `picture with text and shapes` in four steps.

The tools are small. `begin-frame` and `end-frame` bracket a drawing pass. `text/draw` and `fb/text` put strings on the surface. `paint-emoji` and `paint-clear` handle emoji and cleanup. That is enough for a title screen. Chapter 6 will start moving pictures in a loop; here we get one picture right.

## Why the frame lib exists

A picture is easy to describe: it is a rectangle full of colored pixels. The hard part is making the description match what the screen shows. Different displays have different pixel densities, different color models, different refresh rates.

Motoi hides all of that behind a single abstraction: the surface. You paint onto the surface with whatever verbs you like. When you call `end-frame`, Motoi hands the surface to whatever backend is running — a browser canvas, a terminal grid, a headless test buffer — and asks the backend to show it. Your painting code does not know or care which backend is on the other side. This is the same shape Chapter 1 of Book of Composition calls the round-trip: the picture and the code that made it live in the same file, in the same shape, addressable from both sides.

## Problem 1 — Draw one word in the middle of the screen

Four lines. `begin-frame` opens the pass. `text/draw` writes the word. `end-frame` commits.

```
(begin-frame 'main)

(text/draw \"HELLO\"
           at:    (list 160 120)
           color: 'petal-pink
           font:  'big
           align: 'center)

(end-frame 'main)
;; => 'ok  (the word HELLO appears centered on surface 'main)
```

The `at:` keyword takes an `(x y)` position in pixels. `(160 120)` is roughly the middle of a 320×240 surface. `color:` accepts named palette colors (`'petal-pink`, `'mint`, `'brown`) or hex codes like `#xff0000`. `align: 'center` centers the string on the x coordinate; without it the text starts at x.

That is your first picture. If you close the terminal and reopen it, the file remembers everything you wrote — the runtime does not. Painting is a fresh act every frame.

## Problem 2 — A title, a subtitle, and a decorative rule below

Now stack three pieces at three positions. Add a horizontal bar below by painting a solid-color pixel row via `paint-rect`.

```
(begin-frame 'main)

(text/draw \"Motoi Scheme\"
           at:    (list 160 80)
           color: 'petal-pink
           font:  'big
           align: 'center)

(text/draw \"a small language for one small mind\"
           at:    (list 160 110)
           color: 'moss-green
           font:  'default
           align: 'center)

(paint-rect (list 40 130) (list 240 2) 'earth-brown)

(text/draw \"press any key to begin\"
           at:    (list 160 200)
           color: 'earth-brown
           font:  'tiny
           align: 'center)

(end-frame 'main)
```

Notice the three fonts. `'big` for the title, `'default` for the subtitle, `'tiny` for the hint at the bottom. That is a common shape for a title screen — one loud element, one calm element, one small element. If it feels too crowded, drop one. If it feels too sparse, add one.

`paint-rect` takes an `(x y)` origin and a `(width height)` size. Height `2` is thin — a decorative rule, not a bar. Widening the height to `20` would give you a nameplate.

If you want to check your alignment, `text/measure` returns the pixel size of a string before you paint it:

```
(define subtitle \"a small language for one small mind\")
(define size (text/measure subtitle font: 'default))
(display size)
;; => (218 8)   ;; width 218, height 8
```

That tells you the subtitle is 218 pixels wide. If you want it centered but do not want to trust the `align:` keyword, compute `(x = (- 160 (/ 218 2)))` = `51`, and pass that.

## Problem 3 — A splash screen with an emoji, a color palette bar, and framed borders

Now compose. Use `paint-emoji` for the icon, `paint-rect` in a loop for the palette strip, and four `paint-rect` calls for the border.

```
(define palette
  (list 'petal-pink 'moss-green 'earth-brown
        'mint 'rose 'daffodil 'sky-blue))

(define (draw-border)
  (paint-rect (list 0   0)  (list 320   2) 'earth-brown)
  (paint-rect (list 0 238)  (list 320   2) 'earth-brown)
  (paint-rect (list 0   0)  (list   2 240) 'earth-brown)
  (paint-rect (list 318 0)  (list   2 240) 'earth-brown))

(define (draw-palette-bar)
  (let loop ((cs palette) (x 60))
    (if (null? cs)
        'done
        (begin
          (paint-rect (list x 220) (list 28 10) (car cs))
          (loop (cdr cs) (+ x 30))))))

(begin-frame 'main)

(draw-border)

(paint-emoji '🌸 (list 160 90) size: 48)

(text/draw \"Motoi Scheme\"
           at:    (list 160 150)
           color: 'petal-pink
           font:  'big
           align: 'center)

(draw-palette-bar)

(end-frame 'main)
```

Two new patterns landed.

First: `draw-border` and `draw-palette-bar` are named subroutines. Neither is a big function. Both are much easier to read than four `paint-rect` calls buried in the middle of the frame block. Any time you find yourself painting more than three primitives for a single logical element, name it.

Second: the palette loop uses named `let` — the same `let loop (...)` shape you saw as an accumulator recursion in Chapter 4. It walks the list of colors, painting one small swatch per element, advancing `x` by 30 each time. Seven colors, one function.

`paint-emoji` takes a quoted emoji glyph, a position, and an optional `size:` in pixels. Emoji land as bitmaps at that size; the compositor blends them with anything else you draw.

## Problem 4 (pro) — A responsive HUD that resizes with the viewport

Real screens come in different sizes. If you hard-code coordinates for `320×240`, your HUD breaks the moment someone runs your cart at `640×480`. The fix: ask the viewport for its dimensions and paint relative to them.

```
(define (draw-hud score lives)
  (let* ((vp    (viewport))
         (w     (list-ref vp 2))
         (h     (list-ref vp 3))
         (pad   8)
         (right (- w pad))
         (bottom (- h pad)))

    (begin-frame 'main)

    ;; top-left: score
    (text/draw (string-append \"score: \" (number->string score))
               at:    (list pad pad)
               color: 'petal-pink
               font:  'default
               align: 'left)

    ;; top-right: lives (as hearts)
    (let loop ((i 0) (x (- right (* 3 (- lives 1)))))
      (if (= i lives)
          'done
          (begin
            (paint-emoji '❤ (list x pad) size: 12)
            (loop (+ i 1) (+ x 14)))))

    ;; bottom-center: hint
    (text/draw \"[space] jump   [←→] move\"
               at:    (list (/ w 2) bottom)
               color: 'earth-brown
               font:  'tiny
               align: 'center)

    (end-frame 'main)))

(draw-hud 1200 3)
```

`viewport` returns `(x y w h)` for the current camera. We destructure `w` and `h` and place elements relative to them. Now `draw-hud` works whether the screen is 320 wide or 3200 wide.

`let*` is like `let` except each binding can see the ones before it. That lets us define `right` in terms of `w` without nesting three `let`s.

The heart loop is the second `let loop` in this chapter — the shape shows up so often it deserves its own place in your muscle memory.

## Capstone — A pause overlay that dims the background and centers a message

```
(define (draw-pause-overlay message)
  (let* ((vp (viewport))
         (w  (list-ref vp 2))
         (h  (list-ref vp 3)))

    (begin-frame 'main)

    ;; dim the whole screen with a semi-transparent rect
    (paint-rect (list 0 0) (list w h) 'shadow-veil)

    ;; box to hold the message
    (let ((bx (- (/ w 2) 100))
          (by (- (/ h 2)  30))
          (bw 200)
          (bh 60))
      (paint-rect (list bx by) (list bw bh) 'ink-black)
      (paint-rect (list bx by) (list bw 2)  'petal-pink)
      (paint-rect (list bx (+ by bh -2)) (list bw 2) 'petal-pink))

    ;; the message
    (text/draw message
               at:    (list (/ w 2) (/ h 2))
               color: 'petal-pink
               font:  'big
               align: 'center)

    (text/draw \"press [p] to resume\"
               at:    (list (/ w 2) (+ (/ h 2) 18))
               color: 'moss-green
               font:  'tiny
               align: 'center)

    (end-frame 'main)))

(draw-pause-overlay \"paused\")
```

Read the composition. First we dim everything with a full-screen semi-transparent rect (assuming `'shadow-veil` is a palette color with alpha). Then we draw the message box — one filled rect, two thin pink rules top and bottom for style. Then the title and the sub-message in the box.

The whole overlay is one function. The only argument is the message. If tomorrow you want a `game over` overlay, you call `(draw-pause-overlay \"game over\")` and swap the resume-hint text. That is a small function doing one clear job. That is the shape.

## What's next

You can paint. Chapter 6 turns painting into animation. `big-bang`, `on-tick`, and `to-draw` — the three verbs that turn a still frame into a running loop. Once you have a loop, every static example in this chapter becomes a frame in a movie.
")
